 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 1804<br> <font color=#333333>(9/13/02 6:22:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=691.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   A few cents worth...</span><hr size=1> I have not worked with beastlords much, and have only skimmed the boards, but based on my principles for class balance which I have applied to mages, I think it is only fair that beastlords be adequate damage dealers.  In that way, they have a role both in groups and raids.<br>
<br>
Beastlords are in an awkward position.  Their role is ill-defined and their class is incomplete.<br>
<br>
My gut feeling is that while their pets might need some shoring up, I would think the emphasis should be on making beastlords better at melee.  Just looking at their skills, my impression was one largely of absence.  They do not seem to get many goodies from their monkish parent class.<br>
<br>
If the emphasis is placed on pets, then their role on a raid is to substitute for another pet class (assuming pets are viable), and to be honest, there is little room there.  There seems to me to be much more demand and opportunity for melees, on the other hand, and so that is where I would see beastlords moving towards.<br>
<br>
While their warders obviously play a greater role than a shadow knight's, druid's, or shaman's pet, it seems to me that given self-sulficiency in melee, their pets should not be as powerful as necromancer or mage pets.<br>
<br>
I will admit to some ignorance of necromancers and beastlords, and seeing things primarily through the lens of being a mage.<br>
<br>
But the lack of class AA skills and the general incompleteness of the beastlord class surely must lead to frustration, if not desparation, and I am not threatened at all by their explorations and speculations about how they might best better themselves.<br>
<br>
